>
  <p>
    Hi, I'm <strong>Advik Jain</strong> — a student, stargazer, and the person behind The Backyard Astrophysicist.
  </p>

  <p>
    I've been fascinated by the night sky for as long as I can remember. There's something about standing outside, looking up, and realising that the light hitting your eyes left its source millions of years ago — it makes everything feel both enormous and intimate at the same time.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this blog</h2>

  <p>
    I started this as a place to write about the things I was learning — not as an expert, but as someone genuinely curious. Astronomy is full of ideas that are hard to wrap your head around: curved spacetime, quantum uncertainty, the sheer scale of the observable universe. Writing about them helps me understand them better, and hopefully makes them a little more accessible for anyone reading along.
  </p>

  <p>
    Posts cover everything from what's visible in tonight's sky, to deep dives into cosmological theory, to the history of how we figured any of this out in the first place.
  </p>

  <h2>The setup</h2>

  <p>
    I do most of my observing from my backyard — hence the name. No fancy observatory, just a telescope, a red flashlight, and a lot of patience waiting for clouds to clear.
  </p>

  <h2>Get in touch</h2>

  <p>
    If something here sparked a thought, or you want to talk about space, science, or anything in between — find me wherever you found this blog. I'd love to hear from fellow stargazers.
  </p>

  <p style="font-style:italic;color:var(--text-secondary);font-family:var(--font-display);font-size:1.15rem;margin-top:2.5rem;">
    "The cosmos is within us. We are made of star-stuff."<br />— Carl Sagan
  </p>
